defaultgive you some background to the thinking, Chair, because I was part of the NHS management board th
defaultat considered these originally? 
defaultAdmissions had been rising at 4% to 4.4% per year for about eight consecutive years
default,
default and we felt that acute trusts had no real incentive to h
defaultelp keep people at home who didn’
defaultt need to be in hospital. So we agreed to split the tariff in such a way that anything over the 2008
default&#x2011;
default2009 baseline in terms of activity would only be paid for at 30% of the tariff rate
default;
default the remaining 70% would be put into a pot and the trust would engage in discussion with commissioners on how that 70% could be used. That became effective in the operating framework for the NHS in 2010
default&#x2011;
default2011.
default 
defaultMonitor subsequently reviewed that strategy to see whether it had any impact
default.
default 
defaultW
defaulthat we 
defaultsaw
default almost immediately was a very rapid reduction to less than 1% in the growth of admissions.
default 
defaultWhat has been a bit more tricky
default, frankly, over the last three years during the transition has been to really work out whether that money has been actually used for that purpose. We are embarking on new measures to radiolabel that in a way that makes it absolutely identifiable. 
defaultIn May last year Barbara 
defaultHakin
default, as director of operations, wrote out to the urgent 
defaultcare 
defaultworking groups saying that they should have responsibility for ensuring how that money is used. You will recall from discussions last time that the urgent care working groups are, if you like, groups of people who have a vested interest in ensuring that local urgent care works properly
default—
defaultlocal authorities, commissioners, providers
default,
default NHS England, Monitor and the TDA.
default 
defaultor 2014 we have clearly identified this money in the CCG budgets. We have determined that it should be used by the urgent care working groups
default,
default and that will be assured by NHS England. 
defaultOne of the misconceptions that 
defaultare
default around is that all emergency admissions are being paid at only 30% of the rate. What it 
defaultreally 
defaultamounts to in real terms is only 3% of the urgent admission activity. 
defaultSo, f
defaultor the average trust
default,
default we estimate that that would work out broadly 
defaultin
default the order of about £1.5 million. This is not something new and we will be looking at it over the course of the coming months.
