defaultQ6 default&#xa0; 
defaultCharlotte Leslie:default 
defaultThank you very much for coming. The public are understandably concerned that our A and E system needs to be resilient to meet a winter crisis. Can you give reassurance to the public that the system is more resilient than it was last winter?
defaultProfessor Sir Bruce Keoghdefault: 
defaultI think we can. The first thing that I think was different was that this year we started planning for winter much earlier than we had done for previous years. We started planning in May. The second thing that we have done as part of this is put urgent care working groups into place, and I have already alluded to that. The next thing that we have done is put national oversight on to those urgent care working groups
default,
default so that we have Monitor, the TDA, the Association of Directors of Adult Social Services and so forth, who will tackle problems that have been identified by the urgent care working groups. They also provide oversight of local plans for those groups. 
defaultWhat we have also done differently is 
defaultthat we have 
defaultgiven the winter moneys somewhat earlier this year. Normally they are given out towards the tail end of the year. This time we have given two lots. The first lot we gave in September, which was £250 million
default,
default and 
defaultthen 
defaultthat was subsequently supplemented in November by another £150 million. What is different with the moneys this time is that they have been given to those communities where we think the patients are most at risk of problems in winter. That money is not being given just to the hospitals
default; i
defaultt is being given to the communities 
defaultthat
default are served by those hospitals
default. So 
default£371 million of that £400 million has been given to communities; £15 million has been given to help beef up 111 in anticipation of additional calls; £14 million has been given to ambulance services; and £7 million has been given to specialised services because there are some specialised services which come under particular pressure over winter. Obvious examples would be adult intensive care
default unit
default, neonatal intensive care and ECMO
default,
default which is a pretty complicated process for putting oxygen into people
default’s blood when they can’
defaultt breathe on their own. 
defaultThe other thing 
defaultthat 
defaultwe are doing which I think is different this year is being utterly transparent about the data. We are putting it out on a weekly basis in a way that we have not done before
default,
default so that the public, the media and, most importantly I think, local communities can scrutinise it. We have also started to look at how the private sector might be engaged in the event of a surge through hospitals coming in through A and E. One of the issues under consideration is that
default,
default when the going gets rough in winter
default,
default often one of the big impacts is on elective care
default, so
default waiting lists start to drift out
default; could 
defaultelective care be shifted more into the private sector
default?
default Also
default,
default Barbara 
defaultHakin
default has had meetings not only with the private sector but also 
defaultwith 
defaultthe voluntary sector to see what they can do to help. 
defaultI think w
defaulte are certainly better prepared than any winter that I have been involved with before, but I think it would be foolish to be complacent because there are always things that can pop up like outbreaks of flu or 
defaultnorovirus
default or something.
